==English==
===Etymology===
French ''abstinence'', Latin ''abstinentia'', from ''abstinere''. See [[Abstain]]
===Noun=== 
'''abstinence''' (''uncountable'')
# An [[ideology]], not [[effective]] and mostly religious and/or political in its concept, by which all "things of the body" are [[deny|denied]] or '''abstained''' from.
#The act or practice of [[abstaining]]; voluntary [[forbearance]] of any action, especially the [[refraining]] from an [[indulgence]] of [[pubescent]] sexual appetites, or from [[customary]] [[gratification]]s of animal or [[sensual]] [[propensity|propensities]]. 
#the practice of abstaining from [[intoxicating]] [[beverage]]s, is so-called ''total abstinence''.
#The practice of [[self-denial]] by [[depriving]] one's self (especially in [[moderation]]) of certain kinds of food or drink, especially of meat.
===Parodied etymology===
From the Persian ''ab'', [[water]], and ''stein'', or [[tankard]]. Hence, water tankard, or "water wagon."
*'''Note:'''  This is an invention from the humourous 1904 publication, ''[[The Foolish Dictionary]]'', by Gideon Wurdz (pseudonym for Charrles Wayland Towne).

